<subsection xml:id="subsec-volume-of-prisms" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Volume of Prisms</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_ot8lxf7i">
            <p xml:id="auto_7rg2hucd">
            <dl>
                <li xml:id="auto_6bbyh7g2">
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_ncmedls8">
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ij7bqr0b">
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_or6f3jmh">
                        2.8 Volume
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_wzskbt3p">
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_dwu2tn2m">
                        Calculate the volume of prisms using the formula Volume = Area of base × Height
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_mnjqywdd" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_wf0uispk">
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_g4yirwyp" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_9jh14z0d">
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_ro5ujwz4" component="lesson-plan">
                <p xml:id="auto_ijt4dl33"> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li xml:id="auto_i1810h7u">
                        <p xml:id="auto_jdttr0gn">
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Define volume and identify that a prism has a constant cross-section along its height, leading to the formula Volume = Area of base × Height.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_56l7o6f9">
                        <p xml:id="auto_al299vwj">
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Calculate the volume of rectangular, triangular, and other prisms using the appropriate base area formula multiplied by the height.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_4mr39sob">
                        <p xml:id="auto_ow7afskf">
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Solve real-world problems involving the volume of prisms, such as storage containers, greenhouses, and construction materials.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
    <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p xml:id="auto_eqqzwi59">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/volume/volume-of-prisms.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_sycp3mhu">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/volume/step-by-step-guide_volume-of-prisms.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />



    <introduction xml:id="auto_vrtte7tr">
        <p xml:id="auto_364fk3jc">
            The <term>volume</term> of a three-dimensional shape is the amount of space it occupies,
            measured in cubic units (like cm³, m³). A <term>prism</term> is a solid with two identical
            parallel faces called bases, and flat faces connecting corresponding edges of the bases.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_izjdqer8">
            In this section, we explore how to calculate the volume of prisms by using the area
            of the base and the height of the prism. We begin with rectangular and triangular
            prisms, then extend the idea to any prism.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_1vwjopvs">
            A key principle is that the volume of a prism depends on the area of its base and
            how “deep” that base extends in space.
        </p>
    </introduction>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_p62n88ll">
            <alert>Expected Time:</alert> 15 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_uxjm0zlc">
            <alert>Grouping:</alert> Organise learners into groups of 2–3. Distribute grid paper, rulers, and unit cubes (or square cut-outs).
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_uwrpw45r">
            <alert>Teacher Facilitation Questions:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_zz1gp66v">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_hltkesiu">
                    <p xml:id="auto_hgthmis8"><q>How many squares cover the base?</q> (Expected: 12)</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_uyywpkgn">
                    <p xml:id="auto_cro8kz2g"><q>How many cubes total when we stack 5 layers?</q> (Expected: 60)</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_votesfzs">
                    <p xml:id="auto_c4u8ke50"><q>What pattern connects base area, height, and total cubes?</q></p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_369easld">
            <alert>Expected Discovery:</alert> Learners should articulate that Total cubes = Base area × Height.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_ga3z2j3u">
            <alert>Support for Struggling Groups:</alert> Guide learners to draw the rectangular base first, count unit squares one by one, then physically stack layers and count again.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_7t05bp7q">
            <alert>Early Finishers:</alert> Ask <q>How would the volume change if the height doubled? If the base dimensions doubled?</q>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <activity xml:id="auto_8zvy7b0z">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_kw3716vb">
                <term>Work in groups:</term> Form groups of <m>2</m> or <m>3</m> students.
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_nmgym727">
                <term>Materials:</term> Grid/graph paper, ruler and a paper made one unit cube (or square cut-outs)
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_7o64vgg9">
                <term>Instructions:</term>
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_oj2g4bb2">
                Consider the rectangular base below:
            </p>

            <image width="45%">
                <latex-image label="rectangular-base-visual">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.6]
                        \draw[step=1cm,gray!40,very thin] (0,0) grid (4,3);
                        \draw[thick] (0,0) rectangle (4,3);
                        \node[below] at (2,0) {$4$ units};
                        \node[left] at (0,1.5) {$3$ units};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>

            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li xml:id="auto_io28c9y5">Count the number of unit squares in the base.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_2hc0nh0i">Verify your answer using multiplication.</li>
            </ol>

            <p xml:id="auto_pmrykejv">
                Now imagine stacking identical layers to form a prism of height <m>5</m> units.
            </p>

            <image width="45%">
                <latex-image label="rectangular-prism-visual">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.6]
                        \draw[thick] (0,0) rectangle (4,3);
                        \draw[latex-latex] (0,-0.5) -- (4,-0.5)
                            node[midway,below] {$4$};
                        \draw[latex-latex] (-0.5,0) -- (-0.5,3)
                            node[midway,left] {$3$};
                        \draw[very thick, ->] (4,3) -- (4.8,5)
                            node[right] {$5$ units};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>

            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li xml:id="auto_y8wqvp58">How many layers are stacked?</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_bzhd4c9m">How many unit cubes are in the entire prism?</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_qr37r2if">Verify your answer using multiplication.</li>
            </ol>

            <p xml:id="auto_9t1830sh">
                What relationship do you observe between:
                <ul>
                    <li xml:id="auto_cwyz7s5p">Area of the base,</li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_alghcifh">Height of the prism, and</li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_q5zg7bdp">Total number of unit cubes in the prism?</li>
                </ul>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>

   
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_r2a9omuj">
            <alert>Expected Time:</alert> 10 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_m2us6bdg">
            <alert>Transition:</alert> After groups share their findings, formalise the discovery: <q>You have all discovered that Volume = Area of base × Height. Let us now see how this works for different types of prisms.</q>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_bwt0gj2k">
            <alert>Key Teaching Points:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_6barr2n2">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_w6k2shc3">
                    <p xml:id="auto_ny54i4oa">Emphasise that volume is <q>how many unit cubes fit inside</q>.</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_zvtd67ge">
                    <p xml:id="auto_wagtw1z4">Connect multiplication to repeated addition of layers.</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_dg5lvhgz">
                    <p xml:id="auto_u1byjy1c">Stress that the formula works for ANY base shape (rectangle, triangle, pentagon, etc.).</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_iyrfi87q">
                    <p xml:id="auto_6v9teu1v">Highlight units: linear (cm, m), area (cm², m²), volume (cm³, m³). Ensure all dimensions use the same unit before calculating.</p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_1xx2s4sy">
            <alert>Specific Prism Formulas (teacher reference):</alert>
        </p>
        <tabular top="medium" bottom="medium" left="medium" right="medium">
            <row header="yes">
                <cell>Prism Type</cell>
                <cell>Base Area Formula</cell>
                <cell>Volume Formula</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Rectangular Prism (Cuboid)</cell>
                <cell><m>A = l \times w</m></cell>
                <cell><m>V = l \times w \times h</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Cube</cell>
                <cell><m>A = s^2</m></cell>
                <cell><m>V = s^3</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Triangular Prism</cell>
                <cell><m>A = \frac{1}{2} b \times h</m></cell>
                <cell><m>V = \frac{1}{2} b \times h \times H</m></cell>
            </row>
        </tabular>
    </axiom>

     <insight xml:id="auto_zihi17rk">
        <p xml:id="auto_n3k6kjdf">
            The number of unit cubes that fit inside a prism depends on the area of the base
            and the height (depth) of the prism.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_hgxjm98v">
            For any prism:
            <me>
                \textbf{Volume} = \text{Area of base} \times \text{Height}
            </me>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_054ajeev">
            This formula works regardless of the shape of the base (rectangle, triangle,
            or any polygon), as long as the cross-section is constant along the height.
        </p>
    </insight>


    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Practice and Application</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_ah6fj6c8">
            <alert>Expected Time:</alert> 15 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_tlmw4clb">
            <alert>Teacher Guidance:</alert> Walk through worked examples using the two-step approach: (1) Find base area, (2) Multiply by height. Encourage learners to write both steps explicitly.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_tf3gn6vj">
            <alert>Monitoring:</alert> Circulate during individual practice. Watch for learners who:
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_pt96ierz">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_sybfus2g">
                    <p xml:id="auto_58rdf33t">Forget to find the base area first (jump straight to multiplying all three dimensions incorrectly).</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_6z12b2lu">
                    <p xml:id="auto_d95nq8pv">Mix up the triangle height with the prism height in triangular prisms.</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_90fy9xca">
                    <p xml:id="auto_7j0zezt3">Use inconsistent units.</p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <example xml:id="auto_5wxn9ezf">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_2s4q3xt9">
                Find the volume of a triangular prism whose base is a triangle with
                area <m>12\ \text{cm}^2</m> and height <m>10\ \text{cm}</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_llscwwm6">
                Volume = <me>12 \times 10 = 120\ \text{cm}^3</me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
        <example xml:id="auto_rmgc8d08">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_6sfdb42s">
                Finding the volume of a triangular prism.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_xm2fqdgu">
            Step 1: Find the area of the base
            <md>
                <mrow> \textbf{area of triangle =}\amp \frac{1}{2}b \times h</mrow>
                <mrow>= \amp \frac{1}{2} \times 9\, \text{cm} \times 12 \, \text{cm} </mrow>
                <mrow> = \amp 54 \, \text{cm}^2 </mrow>
            </md> 
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_t0qipkn6">
                Step 2: Multiply the area of the base by the height of the solid to find the volume
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_42wkv14s">
                <md>
                    <mrow> \text{Volume} = \amp \text{Base Area} \times \text{height}</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp \frac{1}{2}b \times h \times H</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 54 \, \text{cm}^2\times 25\, \text{cm} </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 1350 \, \text{cm}^3 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_l6dscc8m">
            The volume of the triangular prism is <m>1350 \, \text{cm}^3</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <p xml:id="auto_2cbnq5rh">
        Now let's extend this to a prism with any polygon as a base.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="auto_yozlren0">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_xsq9ay5k">
                A pentagonal prism has a base area of <m>20\ \text{m}^2</m> and a height of <m>7\ \text{m}</m>. Find its volume.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_tk8ovcmd">
                Volume = <me>20 \times 7 = 140\ \text{m}^3</me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
